---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GeneratorShell from '../../components/GeneratorShell.astro';

const title = 'YAML to JSON — Free Converter | Genfy';
const description = 'Turn YAML into JSON instantly in the browser. Supports scalars, lists, nested maps and comments. 100% local.';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Why convert YAML to JSON?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'To process YAML configs in JavaScript code, send them to APIs that only accept JSON, or inspect them with tools that understand JSON but not YAML.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What does this converter support?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The most common syntax: scalars (strings, numbers, booleans, null), hyphen-prefixed lists, nested maps, and # comments. It does not support anchors/aliases or custom tags.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Why does YAML use indentation?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'YAML was designed to be human-readable. Indentation replaces braces and brackets, reducing visual noise. But it also makes YAML sensitive to spacing errors — one stray space breaks everything.' } },
  ],
};
---
<Layout title={title} description={description} lang="en" schema={faqSchema} withSidebar={true}>
  <GeneratorShell lang="en" tag="Data" title="YAML to JSON"
    intro="Paste YAML and get equivalent JSON. Handy for Kubernetes manifests, GitHub Actions, Docker Compose and any YAML you need to process as JSON.">

    <div slot="tool">
      <label for="yj-in">YAML</label>
      <textarea id="yj-in" rows="10" style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.9rem;"># Sample config
name: Genfy
version: 1.0
features:
  - markdown
  - json
  - yaml
database:
  host: localhost
  port: 5432
  active: true</textarea>
      <button id="yj-gen" class="btn btn-primary" type="button" style="margin-top:1rem;">Convert</button>
      <button id="yj-copy" class="btn btn-ghost" type="button">Copy</button>
      <div id="yj-status" class="yj-status"></div>
      <label for="yj-out" style="margin-top:1rem;">JSON</label>
      <textarea id="yj-out" rows="10" readonly style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.9rem;"></textarea>
    </div>

    <div slot="content">
      <h2>YAML: human-readable, parser-strict</h2>
      <p>
        YAML (recursive acronym for "YAML Ain't Markup Language") was born in 2001 as an XML alternative for configs. Big idea: use indentation instead of braces or brackets to denote hierarchy. The result reads like a bullet list rather than code. That's why Kubernetes, Docker Compose, GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Ansible and most modern devops tools use it.
      </p>

      <h2>Why convert to JSON</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>JavaScript processing.</strong> Browsers parse JSON natively; YAML needs an external library of several KB.</li>
        <li><strong>APIs.</strong> Almost every REST API speaks JSON. If your config is YAML, you must convert.</li>
        <li><strong>Validation with existing tools.</strong> JSON Schema is mature; YAML equivalents are less common.</li>
        <li><strong>Version diffs.</strong> YAML diffs can be misleading because of indentation; minified JSON diffs are always clear.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Typical use cases</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Inspecting a Kubernetes manifest.</strong> Convert to JSON to view it in an API tool or run jq over it.</li>
        <li><strong>Migrating config to a JSON-only system.</strong> Plenty of legacy still expects JSON.</li>
        <li><strong>Test snapshots.</strong> Snapshotting structures as JSON is easier in testing.</li>
        <li><strong>Posting to a REST endpoint.</strong> Some APIs accept YAML but most don't.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Limitations of this converter</h2>
      <p>
        It supports the most common syntax that covers 95% of cases: scalars (strings, numbers, booleans, null), hyphen-prefixed lists, nested maps with colons, and <code>#</code> comments. It does NOT support advanced YAML features like anchors (<code>&amp;</code>), aliases (<code>*</code>), custom tags (<code>!!str</code>), multi-document streams (<code>---</code>) or mixed flow style. For those cases, use a full library like js-yaml.
      </p>

      <h2>Common YAML traps</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tab indentation.</strong> YAML allows only spaces. Mixing tabs and spaces breaks the parser.</li>
        <li><strong>Accidental booleans.</strong> "yes", "no", "on", "off", "y", "n" are parsed as booleans. To keep the literal string, quote it.</li>
        <li><strong>Numbers that look like strings.</strong> "012" is parsed as octal in YAML 1.1 — quote it.</li>
        <li><strong>The "Norway problem."</strong> Norway's ISO code is "NO" and YAML turns it into false. Famous saga: <code>countries: [NO, NL]</code> ends up as <code>[false, "NL"]</code>.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>YAML vs JSON: which to use</h2>
      <p>
        For config a human will hand-edit, YAML is more readable. For data flowing between machines, JSON is stricter and faster to parse. Good practice: write configs in YAML but compile to JSON at build time and serve JSON in production. Cuts surprises from ambiguous types and improves parser performance.
      </p>

      <h2>Security tips</h2>
      <p>
        YAML has a complicated security history: it can execute arbitrary code via tags if the parser supports it (CVEs in Ruby psych, Python pyyaml). When parsing untrusted YAML, use a "safe" loader that only allows basic types. This converter never executes code under any circumstances.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div slot="faq">
      <details><summary>Why convert YAML to JSON?</summary><p>For JavaScript processing without libraries, posting to JSON-only APIs, or validating with JSON Schema.</p></details>
      <details><summary>What does this converter support?</summary><p>Scalars, lists, nested maps, comments. No anchors, aliases or custom tags.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Why does YAML use indentation?</summary><p>To be more readable than JSON or XML. The trade-off is spacing-sensitivity.</p></details>
    </div>
  </GeneratorShell>
</Layout>

<style>
  .yj-status { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; min-height: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-soft); }
</style>

<script>
  const inEl = document.getElementById('yj-in') as HTMLTextAreaElement;
  const out = document.getElementById('yj-out') as HTMLTextAreaElement;
  const status = document.getElementById('yj-status') as HTMLDivElement;
  const genBtn = document.getElementById('yj-gen') as HTMLButtonElement;
  const copyBtn = document.getElementById('yj-copy') as HTMLButtonElement;

  function coerce(v: string): any {
    v = v.trim();
    if (v === '' || v === '~' || v.toLowerCase() === 'null') return null;
    if (v === 'true' || v === 'True' || v === 'TRUE') return true;
    if (v === 'false' || v === 'False' || v === 'FALSE') return false;
    if ((v.startsWith('"') && v.endsWith('"')) || (v.startsWith("'") && v.endsWith("'"))) return v.slice(1, -1);
    if (/^-?\d+$/.test(v)) return parseInt(v, 10);
    if (/^-?\d+\.\d+$/.test(v) || /^-?\d+(\.\d+)?[eE][+-]?\d+$/.test(v)) return parseFloat(v);
    return v;
  }

  function parseYAML(text: string): any {
    const lines = text.split('\n').map(l => l.replace(/\s*#.*$/, '')).filter(l => l.trim());
    const stack: { indent: number; value: any; key?: string }[] = [{ indent: -1, value: {} }];

    for (const raw of lines) {
      const indent = raw.length - raw.trimStart().length;
      const line = raw.trim();
      while (stack.length > 1 && stack[stack.length - 1].indent >= indent) stack.pop();
      const top = stack[stack.length - 1];

      if (line.startsWith('- ')) {
        const rest = line.slice(2).trim();
        if (!Array.isArray(top.value)) {
          if (top.key !== undefined && stack.length >= 2) {
            const parent = stack[stack.length - 2].value;
            parent[top.key] = [];
            top.value = parent[top.key];
          }
        }
        if (rest.includes(': ')) {
          const m = rest.match(/^([^:]+):\s*(.*)$/);
          if (m) {
            const obj: any = {};
            if (m[2]) obj[m[1]] = coerce(m[2]);
            top.value.push(obj);
            stack.push({ indent: indent + 2, value: obj });
          }
        } else {
          top.value.push(coerce(rest));
        }
      } else {
        const m = line.match(/^([^:]+):\s*(.*)$/);
        if (!m) continue;
        const key = m[1].trim(), val = m[2];
        if (val === '') {
          const obj: any = {};
          top.value[key] = obj;
          stack.push({ indent, value: obj, key });
        } else if (val === '[]') {
          top.value[key] = [];
        } else if (val === '{}') {
          top.value[key] = {};
        } else if (val.startsWith('[') && val.endsWith(']')) {
          top.value[key] = val.slice(1, -1).split(',').map(s => coerce(s.trim()));
        } else {
          top.value[key] = coerce(val);
        }
      }
    }
    return stack[0].value;
  }

  function run() {
    const txt = inEl.value;
    if (!txt.trim()) { out.value = ''; status.textContent = ''; return; }
    try {
      const data = parseYAML(txt);
      out.value = JSON.stringify(data, null, 2);
      status.textContent = '✓ YAML converted';
    } catch (e: any) {
      out.value = '';
      status.textContent = 'Error: ' + (e.message || 'Invalid YAML');
    }
  }
  inEl.addEventListener('input', run);
  genBtn.addEventListener('click', run);
  copyBtn.addEventListener('click', async () => {
    if (!out.value) return;
    await navigator.clipboard.writeText(out.value);
    const t = copyBtn.textContent; copyBtn.textContent = 'Copied!';
    setTimeout(() => { copyBtn.textContent = t; }, 1200);
  });
  run();
</script>
